@startuml gkg_selfmanaged_auth_sequence

skinparam backgroundColor #FFFFFF
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam padding 5
skinparam roundCorner 8
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam sequenceArrowThickness 2
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center

title Hybrid Self-Managed: Auth Flow\n(Cloud-hosted GKG ↔ On-Prem Monolith)

box "Customer On-Premises" #FFF3E0
  actor "User /\nLLM Agent" as user
  participant "GitLab Rails\n(Self-Managed)" as rails
  participant "Gitaly" as gitaly
end box

box "GitLab Cloud Infrastructure" #E8F4FD
  participant "DAP\n(Data Access Proxy)" as dap
  participant "Orbit\n(Graph Query Engine)" as orbit
  participant "Redis\n(Auth Cache)" as redis
  database "ClickHouse\nCloud" as ch
end box

== Query Request ==

user -> rails : Graph query request
rails -> dap : HTTP + JWT\n(user identity + scopes)
dap -> orbit : Forwarded request\n(validated JWT)

== Authorization Check ==

orbit -> redis : Check auth cache\n(traversal_id, user_id)

alt Cache HIT
  redis --> orbit : Cached authorization result
else Cache MISS
  redis --> orbit : No cached result

  orbit -> rails : **HTTP callback: Ability.allowed?**\n//This crosses the network boundary//\n//Cloud → Customer on-prem//
  note right #FFCCCC
    **Challenge 1: Network connectivity**
    Requires stable, low-latency path from
    GitLab cloud back to customer firewall.
    Customer must expose Rails auth endpoint
    or establish a secure tunnel (e.g. VPN,
    Private Link, or reverse proxy).
  end note

  rails --> orbit : Authorization decision\n(allowed/denied + scope)
  note right #FFCCCC
    **Challenge 2: Latency**
    Round-trip to on-prem adds 10-100ms+
    per uncached auth check. Under load,
    this can dominate query time.
  end note

  orbit -> redis : Cache authorization result\n(TTL-bounded)
end

== Query Execution (if authorized) ==

orbit -> ch : Parameterized SQL query
ch --> orbit : Result set

orbit --> dap : Query response
dap --> rails : Response
rails --> user : Graph data

== Batch Redaction (row-level) ==

orbit -> rails : **HTTP callback: batch redaction**\n//Filters rows user cannot see//\n//Also crosses network boundary//
note right #FFCCCC
  **Challenge 3: Redaction at scale**
  Every result set may require a
  round-trip to on-prem Rails for
  row-level permission filtering.
  Batching helps but doesn't eliminate
  the cross-boundary call.
end note

rails --> orbit : Redacted row set
orbit --> dap : Final filtered response
dap --> rails : Response
rails --> user : Redacted graph data

== Key Risks ==

note over user, ch #FFE0E0
  **Summary of cross-boundary auth challenges:**

  1. **Firewall / network policy** — customer must allow inbound connections
     from GitLab cloud to their on-prem Rails instance for auth callbacks.
  2. **Latency budget** — every cache miss adds a cross-network round-trip;
     cold-cache bursts (e.g. first query after TTL expiry) can spike P99.
  3. **Availability coupling** — if the on-prem monolith is unreachable,
     Orbit cannot authorize queries (fail-open is not acceptable).
  4. **Security posture** — exposing an auth endpoint externally increases
     attack surface; mutual TLS or equivalent is required.
end note

@enduml
